### Step 7: Create a Design System Documentation Page

**Document your customizations** so your team knows what's different from default shadcn:

```tsx
// app/design-system/page.tsx
export default function DesignSystemPage() {
  return (
    <div className="container mx-auto py-12 space-y-12">
      <section>
        <h1 className="text-4xl font-bold mb-4">Our Design System</h1>
        <p className="text-muted-foreground">
          Built on shadcn/ui, customized to match our Figma design system.
        </p>
      </section>

      {/* Colors */}
      <section>
        <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Colors</h2>
        <div className="grid grid-cols-5 gap-4">
          <div className="space-y-2">
            <div className="h-24 bg-primary rounded-lg" />
            <p className="text-sm font-medium">Primary</p>
            <p className="text-xs text-muted-foreground">--primary</p>
          </div>
          <div className="space-y-2">
            <div className="h-24 bg-secondary rounded-lg" />
            <p className="text-sm font-medium">Secondary</p>
            <p className="text-xs text-muted-foreground">--secondary</p>
          </div>
          {/* ... more colors */}
        </div>
      </section>

      {/* Buttons */}
      <section>
        <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Buttons</h2>
        <div className="space-y-4">
          <div>
            <h3 className="text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Variants</h3>
            <div className="flex flex-wrap gap-2">
              <Button variant="default">Default</Button>
              <Button variant="secondary">Secondary</Button>
              <Button variant="outline">Outline</Button>
              <Button variant="ghost">Ghost</Button>
              <Button variant="brand">Brand</Button>
              <Button variant="success">Success</Button>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div>
            <h3 className="text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Sizes</h3>
            <div className="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2">
              <Button size="xs">Extra Small</Button>
              <Button size="sm">Small</Button>
              <Button size="default">Default</Button>
              <Button size="lg">Large</Button>
              <Button size="xl">Extra Large</Button>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      {/* ... more components */}
    </div>
  )
}
```

---

### Step 8: Advanced Customization Techniques

#### **Technique 1: Component Composition**

Create compound components that match your Figma patterns:

```tsx
// components/ui/feature-card.tsx
import { Card, CardHeader, CardTitle, CardDescription, CardContent } from "@/components/ui/card"
import { Badge } from "@/components/ui/badge"
import { Button } from "@/components/ui/button"

// This exact pattern exists in your Figma
export function FeatureCard({ 
  title, 
  description, 
  category,
  cta,
  ...props 
}: FeatureCardProps) {
  return (
    <Card className="group hover:border-primary/50 transition-all" {...props}>
      <CardHeader>
        <Badge variant="secondary" className="w-fit mb-2">{category}</Badge>
        <CardTitle>{title}</CardTitle>
        <CardDescription>{description}</CardDescription>
      </CardHeader>
      <CardContent>
        <Button variant="outline" className="w-full group-hover:border-primary">
          {cta}
        </Button>
      </CardContent>
    </Card>
  )
}

// Usage matches your Figma component
<FeatureCard 
  title="Advanced Analytics"
  description="Track user behavior with detailed insights"
  category="Premium"
  cta="Learn More"
/>
```

#### **Technique 2: CSS Variable Overrides for Specific Sections**

```tsx
// Different section, custom color override
<section 
  className="healthcare-section"
  style={{
    '--primary': '142 76% 36%',        // Green instead of blue
    '--primary-foreground': '0 0% 100%',
  } as React.CSSProperties}
>
  <Button>Healthcare Button</Button>  {/* Will be green! */}
</section>
```

#### **Technique 3: Animation Matching Figma Prototypes**

Add custom animations that match your Figma prototype timings:

```css
/* globals.css */
@keyframes slide-in {
  from {
    opacity: 0;
    transform: translateY(10px);
  }
  to {
    opacity: 1;
    transform: translateY(0);
  }
}

.animate-slide-in {
  animation: slide-in 0.3s ease-out;
}
```

```tsx
// Match your Figma modal animation
import { Dialog, DialogContent } from "@/components/ui/dialog"

<DialogContent className="animate-slide-in">
  {/* ... */}
</DialogContent>
```

---

### Step 9: Using AI to Speed Up Customization

**Use LLM to generate custom shadcn variants:**

```
I need to customize a shadcn/ui Button component to match my Figma design.

Figma Button Specs:
- Border radius: 12px (rounded-xl)
- Font weight: 600 (semibold)
- Height (default): 44px
- Padding X: 24px
- Has subtle shadow on hover
- Has scale animation on press
- Primary color: #3B82F6 (already in CSS vars as --primary)

Current shadcn button:
[Paste current button code]

Generate the customized buttonVariants cva configuration.
```

**LLM generates:**

```tsx
const buttonVariants = cva(
  "inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-xl text-sm font-semibold transition-all duration-200 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring focus-visible:ring-offset-2 disabled:pointer-events-none disabled:opacity-50 active:scale-95",
  {
    variants: {
      variant: {
        default: "bg-primary text-primary-foreground hover:shadow-md",
        // ... rest generated
      },
      size: {
        default: "h-11 px-6",  // 44px height, 24px padding
        // ... rest generated
      }
    }
  }
)
```

---

### Step 10: Maintaining Sync Between Figma and Code

**Workflow for keeping them in sync:**

1. **Design tokens are source of truth**
   - Update Figma variables
   - Export to JSON
   - Run conversion script
   - Update CSS variables

2. **Component changes**
   - Update Figma component
   - Screenshot new specs
   - Ask LLM to update shadcn component
   - Test and deploy

3. **Automation script:**

```bash
#!/bin/bash
# sync-design-tokens.sh

echo "Syncing design tokens from Figma..."

# 1. Export tokens from Figma (via API or manual)
# 2. Convert DTCG JSON to CSS variables
node scripts/tokens-to-css.js

# 3. Update Tailwind config
node scripts/tokens-to-tailwind.js

# 4. Regenerate TypeScript types
npm run generate-types

echo "‚úì Design tokens synced!"
```

---

## Comparison: Generic vs. Branded

**Before Customization (Generic shadcn):**
```tsx
<Button>Click Me</Button>
```
- Looks like every other shadcn site
- Default slate colors
- Standard 6px border radius
- Basic hover state

**After Customization (Your Brand):**
```tsx
<Button>Click Me</Button>
```
- Uses YOUR brand blue (#3B82F6)
- YOUR border radius (12px)
- YOUR font weight (600)
- YOUR hover effects (shadow + lift)
- YOUR spacing (from Figma tokens)
- Matches Figma designs perfectly

**The Power:** Same component API, completely different visual identity.

---

## Quick Reference: Customization Checklist

- [ ] Install shadcn/ui with CSS variables enabled
- [ ] Export design tokens from Figma as DTCG JSON
- [ ] Convert hex colors to HSL format
- [ ] Map tokens to CSS variables in globals.css
- [ ] Update Tailwind config with your scales
- [ ] Customize Button component styles
- [ ] Customize Input component styles
- [ ] Customize Card component styles
- [ ] Add custom variants for brand-specific needs
- [ ] Create compound components for Figma patterns
- [ ] Document your customizations
- [ ] Set up sync workflow
- [ ] Test light/dark mode
- [ ] Test all component states
- [ ] Deploy and monitor

---

**Key Takeaway:** shadcn/ui gives you a production-ready foundation. Your Figma design system gives you brand identity. Combining them gives you the best of both worlds: speed + uniqueness.

---

## Conclusion

This workflow combines Figma's latest features with LLM integration to create a design system that:

1. **Scales:** Variable collections that grow with your product
2. **Flexes:** Slots for dynamic components
3. **Connects:** Code Connect + MCP for design-to-code
4. **Validates:** Check designs + AI guidelines
5. **Performs:** 30-60% faster variable operations
6. **Standards-based:** DTCG 1.0 compliance

The key is establishing a clear token hierarchy, using Figma's native features for structure and export, connecting via MCP for LLM context, and using specific prompts to maintain design system compliance when generating code or designs.

Start small, scale up, and let automation handle synchronization between design and code.
